args: My first impression was that she was a cold and\ndispassionate woman.
So the Wing of War himself has\ndeigned to pay us a visit, mmm?
It is an honor to meet you, Auspex.\nAnd you are...?
You may call me Harle. It's a pleasure\nto make your acquaintance, Basileus.
Do you know why I called you here?
Then let me cut straight to the point.
The man who burned your village\nto the ground is Cardinal Graht.
You have long wanted to know this, yes?
You dug as deep as you could, yet could\nonly learn one of the cardinals was behind\nthe deed. So close...and yet so very far.
You were so hell-bent on revenge that you\neven rose to become the leader of the\napostles. Such determination is touching!
And what do you hope to accomplish\nby telling me this now?
Oh, there's no need to be defensive.\nWe merely want to work with you.
I have a plan that involves Cardinal Graht.\nWhen it is finished, we will be rid of him.

Then you will be executed for the horrible
deeds you committed before becoming an
apostle—including the murder of the
previous Wing of War.
Will you join me and enact your revenge?\nOr will you die without ever giving Graht\nwhat he so richly deserves?
My decision was obvious.\nRevenge was the only thing I cared about,\nso I agreed to help Origa without hesitation.
Origa wanted to revive Satan in order to fight\nagainst the Progenitor.
My ability to interact with other worlds has\nshown me one where the Progenitor wins\nand all possibility is eliminated.
We must not permit that to be.
I didn't understand what she was saying to me.
Why did she want to protect ＂possibility＂?\nWhat was she seeing in the future of this world?
This room is protected by a barrier.\nNot so much as a mouse can get through.
A perfect place for a strategy meeting.\nSpeaking of which, where is that man?

Harle? He's off looking for a Sacred Shard
imbued with the mana of a certain angel.
We need this item in order to perform the
resurrection ceremony.

Sounds like it may be difficult to obtain—
and we also have to resurrect the demons
and prepare the sacrifices. I worry we may
have too many balls in the air here.
Which is why we needed someone\nlike you who would be free to get\nother things done.
Before we begin this plan,\nmay I ask you a question?
Why are you trying to protect possibility?
While this isn't public knowledge,\nthere are tales of your past told by\nsome in the Church.
Your childhood was cruel and unrelenting.\nI hear you were an orphan—one who spent\ndays at a time without food.
When you were finally rescued by an\norphanage, they quickly learned of your\naptitude as an Auspex.
Yet becoming Auspex is a grueling\nprocess where only the strongest\ncandidate survives.
This is not a past one would look fondly\nupon, and it means you know all too well\nhow horrible this world can be.
Were I you, I would not spare a single\nshred of hope for its future.
Yet you are willing to offer your body as\na vessel to Satan in order to protect what\npossibility may exist here.
What is it that drives you so?
Let me ask you this: Did you ever truly \nwish to die?

Your home was razed. You have no one
you can rely on. You have known hunger.
Surely you must have considered death as
an alternative, yet you lived all the same.
Though you cursed your powerlessness\nand did terrible things, you still wanted\nto live. This is why you are here today.
You make your desires real through your\nown strength—and this can only be due\nto the power of possibility.
It seems your circumstances have lead you\nto lose faith in the future and possibility,\nbut I am the opposite.

It was I who overcame the cruel
circumstances thrust upon me.
By my own hand. With my own strength.
I take pride in that.
I know more than anyone how precious\npossibility is—and that is why I will\nprotect it, no matter the cost to myself.
Even though we both crawled up from\nthe wreckage of our own pasts, it appears\nwe wound up taking opposite stances.
So it would seem. You have lived only\nfor revenge, while I long for a world\nfilled with possibility.
You live in the past and I dream of the\nfuture. Who would have thought that such\nopposites could come together?
Origa had something I didn't, and I realized from\nthe bottom of my heart that I wished to see the\nworld she desired.
That was how we spent our days.
Well, if you aren't busy, I was wondering\nif you might...train with me?
Truly?! Oh, wonderful! I will be waiting\nin the courtyard tonight.
Never thought I'd see Basileus agreeing\nto give his juniors lessons. He's sure\nmellowed.
Yes, he clearly feels so much more\nrelaxed these days.
Kinda makes a fellow wonder...\nThink he's got a special someone?
How dare you even suggest something\nso crass! I'm failing you right now.
Pipe down, Faris. If you keep talking like\nthat, Pinon'll realize you've never had a\nrelationship before.
Whoopsie! Looks like ol' Papa Bear\ntook this one a step too far.
And there they go...\nLet's just leave them be, yes?
Still, they're not wrong:\nBasileus HAS changed lately.
He's been listening to our opinions more,\nand even leans on us during missions.
He's become an even bigger asset to\nthe team.
He is everything I strive to be!
Word around the apostles' camp is that\nyou're starting to go soft.
Hmm? I haven't changed at all.
So you haven't even realized?\nYou're quite the character.
You changed after meeting that Auspex.
Now you seem to enjoy yourself around the\napostles—and don't even get me started\non what you're like around HER.
You do understand that you can't make\nfriends with them, yes?
You must betray the apostles, turn Origa\ninto Satan's vessel, and kill Graht.
Those are your ultimate goals, correct?\nAnd getting attached to anything now\nwill only lead to sorrow in the end.
I know this all too well.
